==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slav
<hw>Slav</hw> <pr>(sl⟦aum⟧v <it>or</it> sl⟦acr⟧v)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Slavs</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[A word
originally meaning, intelligible, and used to contrast the people so
called with foreigners who spoke languages unintelligible to the Slavs;
akin to OSlav. <ets>slovo</ets> a word, <ets>slava</ets> fame, Skr.
<ets>⟦cced⟧ru</ets> to hear. Cf. <er>Loud</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>One of a race of people occupying a large part
of Eastern and Northern Europe, including the Russians, Bulgarians,
Roumanians, Servo-Croats, Slovenes, Poles, Czechs, Wends or Sorbs,
Slovaks, etc.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Slave</asp>, and
<asp>Sclav</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slave</ent>⟦br⟧
